------+                                   +----+-----+\n     |  Loup   |    |           |      ^   +--------------+         | Lion     |\n     +---------+    |  Chat     |      |   |   Chien      |         +----------+\n     |         |    +-----------+      +---+--------------+         |          |\n     +---------+    |           |          |              |         +----------+\n                    +-----------+          +--------------+\n\n\n\n','2015-02-22 18:15:24'),(795,'#internet -basis','tout l_internet se pose sur 3types d_operateurs:\n    isp | prestataire de srvc\n    fournisseurs d_access\n    operateur de transport\n\nisp est le proche des internautes\n    ex d_isp:\n        telma, blueline, ...\n    \nechange entre client et isp\n    client donne de l_argent a l_isp\n    isp donne abonnement\n        adresse mail au client\n\nschema basique de l_internet\n                             +----------------------------------------+---------------------------------------+\n        client_internet      |     entreprise   ----+                 |      +--  internaute              ----+--+        operateur de \n ----------------------------+----------------------|-----------------+------+--------------------------------+  |\n                             |    fournisseur       |                 |      +->> prestataire de srvc     --+ <<<+ --+    transport de\n        service_internet     |        d_         <<-+                 +-------------------------------------+-+      |    \n                             |     access                ---+         |                                  <<-+ |<<<<<-+    telecommunication\n-----------------------------+------------------------------|---------+---------------------------------------+\n        reseau_internet      |     operateur de transport  <+               --+                               |\n ----------------------------+------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------+\n                             |   operateur de cablage                       <<+                               |\n                             +--------------------------------------------------------------------------------+\n\nsi un prestataire de srvc donne de l_abonnement a ses clients,\n    il doit etre d_abord etre connectee a internet\n    pour cela, le prestataire de service doit louer une connection_internet \n        a un ( fai | iap ), et doit acheter un nom de domaine\n    \'\n    le nom de domaine est attribuer par icann (apnic + arin + ripe)\n\n(#097 i_thought:\n    client -------->>> fai\n    maintenant c:\n        client ------------>>> prestataire_srvc --------->>> fai\n#098)\n                                                                   \n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-22 19:16:29'),(796,'#so -intro','\nici l_ordi est le travailleur(l_employee)\nPour travailler, l’employé est au centre des traitements,\n    on lui remet dans un dossier le travail à faire(information d_entree)\n    dans un autre dossier il devra mettre le travail fait (informations en sortie)\n     \n                         +------------------+\n        +--------+       |+----------------+|        +-----------+\n        | entree +----->>|| sys de traitmt ++------>>|  sorties  |\n        +--------+       |+----------------+|        +-----------+\n                         +------------------+\n\npour exe son travail, l’employé peut avoir besoin de réaliser des calculs\n    il dispose pour cela d’une calculatrice(unitee de calcul)\n\nl’employé va noter sur un brouillon les instructions qu’il a reçues et qui constituent son __programme__ de travail,\n\nl_employee a besoin de noter a besoin de noter des info sur les donnees dont il va traiter\n    c_est la memorisation_des_instructions(ifk: par ou il s_est arretee la derniere fois)\n    cette memoire vit ----->> c_est la __memoire_vive__\n\nl_employee a besoin de stocker certains informations comme la tva, qu_il va memoriser une fois pour toute\n    c_est une memo qui ne vit pas :: __memo_morte__\n\ncertains info sont trop gd pour etre memorisees de tete par l_employee(catalogue des prix, addr_client, ...)\n    on introduit la memorisation_externe ou auxiliaire\n\n\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-24 09:50:45'),(797,'#binaries -equivalence-power','\n2^-n                    n             2^n\n-------------------------------------------------\n1                       0             1\n0.5                     1             2\n0.25                    2             4\n0.125                   3             8\n0.0625                  4             16\n0.03125                 5             32\n0.015625                6             64\n0.0078125               7             128\n0.00390625              8             256\n0.001953125             9             512\n0.0009765625            10            1024\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-24 10:18:14'),(798,'#binaries -operations','\n            1 1 0 0     |   1 0 0\n                        +---------------\n       -    1 0 0            1        <<<<--- ty no mande voloo\n    -----------------        |\n            0 1 0 0          +--------+\n       -      1 0 0          1        |\n   -------------------                |\n              0 0 0   +---------------+\n                      v\ndonc le resultat est (11)b2\n\nexo:\n    1 0 1 1 0 0 diviser par 1 0 0 egal 1 0 1 1 \n\n====================================================================\n                                        +-----------+\n                                     +--+-----+     |\n(4.25)b10                            |        |     +----- 1 . (1 / 4)\n1.2^2 + 0.2^1 + 0.2^0 + 0.(2^(-1)) + 1.(2^(-2))                |     |\n|                   |   |                     |                +--+--+\n+---+---------------+   +---+-----------------+                   +- = 0.25\n    +---- = 4               +-- = 0.25\n\n\n\n\n2^-n                    n             2^n \n1                       0             1\n0.5                     1             2\n0.25                    2             4\n0.125                   3             8\n0.0625                  4             16\n0.03125                 5             32\n0.015625                6             64\n0.0078125               7             128\n0.00390625              8             256\n0.001953125             9             512\n0.0009765625            10            1024\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-24 10:20:10'),(799,'#so -notion-mot','\n0000 0000 0000 0000 0000 0000 0000 0000\n========================================\n|  |\n+--+\n+--quartet\n\n|       |\n+-------+\n+--octet(demi-mot)\n\n|                  |\n+------------------+\n+-- mot de 16bits\n\n|                                      |\n+--------------------------------------+\n+----------  double_mots\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-24 10:25:24'),(800,'#so -entiers-signees','\nnormalement, (27)b10 = 1 1 0 1 1\n\ndans un entier signee, \n    (27)b10 est 0 1 1 0 1 1\npour que (-27)b10 soit\n    1 1 1 0 1 1\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-24 10:27:50'),(801,'#uml -9-diagrammes','\nselon le livre de morley(UML POUR L’ANALYSE D’UN SYSTÈME D’INFORMATION)\nil y a 9 diagrammes pour uml\n    le livre ne presente que 7 diagrammes\n1  diagramme de classes ;                -+-- pour l_aspect statique du sys\n2  diagramme d’objets ;                  -+\n\n3  diagramme d’états-transitions ;       -+-- pour l_aspect dynamique du sys\n4  diagramme d’activités ;                |\n5  diagramme de collaboration ;           |\n6  diagramme de séquence ;                |\n7  diagramme de cas d’utilisation.       -+\n\n8 le diagramme de composants ;           -+-- pour les informaticiens\n9 le diagramme de déploiement.           -+\n\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-24 10:40:52'),(985,'#uml -tutopoint','\nit is not only a computer_prg which is able to design with uml\n    but even a system in the current_life\n                                                                 -----+\n       +--------+                          +----------------+         |\n       | design +------+     +-------------+ implementation |         |\n       +--------+    +-+-----+--+          +----------------+         |\n                     | use case |                                     |\n    +------------+   +--+----+--+          +---------+                |\n    | deployment +------+    +-------------+ process |                |\n    +------------+                         +---------+                |\n                                                                      |\n                                                                      |\ndesign consists of                                                    |\n    class                                                             |\n    collaboration                                                     |\n    interfaces                                                        |\n                                                                      |\nimplementations means assembled everything to                         |\n    make a complete physical_sys                                      |\n                                                                      |\nprocess defines the flow of the sys                                   |\n                                                                 -----+\n\n\n================================================================================\nmodeling a sys with uml has three types:                                        <<-+\n    u model only the static features of the sys                                    |\n        that means structural modeling                                             |\n    u describe the interaction in the sys                                          |\n        that means behavioral modeling                                             |\n    u describe the overall framework                                               |\n        it contains both structural&behavioral modeling                            |\n================================================================================   |\n                                                                                   |\n                                                                                   |\n                                                                                   |\nfor modeling in structural model, u need                                -----------+ ----+\n    classes,                                                                             |\n        notation: u should know that already                                             |\n    interfaces,                                                                          |\n        notation:                                                                        |\n            +-----------------------+                                                    |\n            |    interf00           |  <<interface>>                                     |\n            +-----------------------+                                                    |\n            |                       |                                                    |\n            |                       |                                                    |\n            |                       |                                                    |\n            |                       |                                                    |\n            +-----------------------+                                                    |\n    objects                                                                              |\n            +-----------------------+    -+---- really the same as the                   |\n            |     Person            |     |        class but class_name is               |\n            +-----++++++------------+     |        underlined                            |\n            |    +name  : String    |     |                                              |\n            |    #id  : int         |     |                                              |\n            |    -                  |     |                                              |\n            +-----------------------+    -+                                              |\n                                                                                         |\n    collaboration,                                                                       |\n        notation: represented by a dotted eclipse                                        |\n    use_case,                                                                            |\n    actor                                                                                |\n        notation:                                                                        |\n    initial_state                                                                        |\n        notation:                                                                        |\n    final_state                                                                          |\n        notation                                                                         |\n    active_class                                                                         |\n        notation is the same as the class but the border is in bold                      |\n    component notation                                                                   |\n    node notation                                                                      --+\n\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-03-14 21:10:34'),(803,'#prolog -charging-files',NULL,NULL,'\nswipl -f /path/file00\n','2015-02-24 14:54:58'),(804,'-predicat #prolog -argument',NULL,NULL,'\nin book of prolog, in error_msg of prolog u may see something like this:\n    =/2     this means, the built-in = in prolog must have 2arg\n        so u can do         =(val00, val00).\n    help/2\n        this means the function _help_ has 2arguments\n','2015-02-24 14:57:12'),(805,'#prolog -matching',NULL,NULL,'\nthose will be true,\n    ?- =(mia, mia).\n    ?- mia=mia.\n    ?- mia = mia.\n    ?- mia= mia.\n    ?- 2 = 2 .\n    ?- \'mia\' = mia.\n\nthose will be false.\n    ?- \'2\' = 2 .\n    \'\n    X = mia , X = vincent .\n','2015-02-24 15:08:59'),(806,'#ff -new-tab','<c-t>',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-24 18:20:43'),(807,'#ff -history',NULL,NULL,'sqlite3 ~/.mozilla/firefox/*.[dD]efault/places.sqlite \"SELECT strftime(\'%d.%m.%Y %H:%M:%S\', visit_date/1000000, \'unixepoch\', \'localtime\'),url FROM moz_places, moz_historyvisits WHERE moz_places.id = moz_historyvisits.place_id ORDER BY visit_date;\"','2015-02-25 04:41:58'),(808,'#network -external#ip #linux',NULL,'dig +short myip.opendns.com @resolver1.opendns.com',NULL,'2015-02-25 04:44:37'),(809,'#linux -get-beep',NULL,NULL,'\ndo not forget to check in gnome-terminal\n    Edit > \'Profile Preferences\' > \'Terminal Bell\'\n\n\n    echo -ne \'\\007\'\n    echo -e \'\\a\'\n','2015-02-25 04:49:47'),(810,'#hardinfo -hoardware-information -tools','\napt-get install hardinfo\nhardinfo\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 05:31:19'),(811,'#cache -gen_c -intro','\nCache is a high-speed access area that can be either a reserved section of main memory or storage device\nThe two main cache types are \n    memory cache \n    disk cache\n\nMemory cache is a portion on memory of high-speed static RAM (SRAM)\n    static RAM (SRAM) and is effective because most programs access the same data or instructions over and over.\n    \'\n    Today, most computers come with L3 cache or L2 cache\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 05:47:59'),(812,'#youtube-dl #yt_dl -select-vid-quality',NULL,'youtube-dl -F link00',NULL,'2015-02-25 05:52:15'),(813,'#youtube-dl #yt_dl -select-vid-quality',NULL,NULL,'\nyoutube-dl -F link00\nout:            ^^---------------+\nu have to wait a little bit.     |\n...                              |\n171         webm      audio only |DASH audio   96k , audio@128k (44100Hz), 19.82MiB (worst)\n140         m4a       audio only |DASH audio  131\n                                 |\n                                 |\nif u want to get the 171  + -----+\n    \'                    v\n    youtube-dl -f 171 link00\n\n','2015-03-12 06:46:02'),(814,'#youtube-dl -installation',NULL,NULL,'\ncheck that your pip is installed\n    apt-cache policy python-pip\n\nif pip is installed, then install youtube-dl\n    sudo pip install youtube-dl\n','2015-02-25 06:03:51'),(815,'#bash -shortcuts',NULL,NULL,'\nBash Keyboard Shortcuts\n\nMoving the cursor:\n\n  Ctrl + a   Go to the beginning of the line (Home)\n  Ctrl + e   Go to the End of the line (End)\n  Ctrl + p   Previous command (Up arrow)\n  Ctrl + n   Next command (Down arrow)\n   Alt + b   Back (left) one word      or use Option+Right-Arrow\n   Alt + f   Forward (right) one word  or use Option+Left-Arrow\n  Ctrl + f   Forward one character\n  Ctrl + b   Backward one character\n  Ctrl + xx  Toggle between the start of line and current cursor position\n\nEditing:\n\n Ctrl + L   Clear the Screen, similar to the clear command\n\n  Alt + Del Delete the Word before the cursor.\n  Alt + d   Delete the Word after the cursor.\n Ctrl + d   Delete character under the cursor\n Ctrl + h   Delete character before the cursor (backspace)\n\n Ctrl + w   Cut the Word before the cursor to the clipboard.\n Ctrl + k   Cut the Line after the cursor to the clipboard.\n Ctrl + u   Cut/delete the Line before the cursor position.\n\n  Alt + t   Swap current word with previous\n Ctrl + t   Swap the last two characters before the cursor (typo).\n Esc  + t   Swap the last two words before the cursor.\n\n ctrl + y   Paste the last thing to be cut (yank)\n  Alt + u   UPPER capitalize every character from the cursor to the end of the current word.\n  Alt + l   Lower the case of every character from the cursor to the end of the current word.\n  Alt + c   Capitalize the character under the cursor and move to the end of the word.\n  Alt + r   Cancel the changes and put back the line as it was in the history (revert).\n ctrl + _   Undo\n \n TAB        Tab completion for file/directory names\n\n    For example, to move to a directory \'sample1\'; Type cd sam ; then press TAB and ENTER.\n    type just enough characters to uniquely identify the directory you wish to open.\n\nHistory:\n\n  Ctrl + r   Recall the last command including the specified character(s)\n             searches the command history as you type.\n             Equivalent to : vim ~/.bash_history. \n  Ctrl + p   Previous command in history (i.e. walk back through the command history)\n  Ctrl + n   Next command in history (i.e. walk forward through the command history)\n   Alt + .   Use the last word of the previous command\n  Ctrl + s   Go back to the next most recent command.\n            (beware to not execute it from a terminal because this will also launch its XOFF).\n  Ctrl + o   Execute the command found via Ctrl+r or Ctrl+s\n  Ctrl + g   Escape from history searching mode\n\nProcess control:\n\n Ctrl + C   Interrupt/Kill whatever you are running (SIGINT)\n Ctrl + l   Clear the screen\n Ctrl + s   Stop output to the screen (for long running verbose commands)\n Ctrl + q   Allow output to the screen (if previously stopped using command above)\n Ctrl + D   Send an EOF marker, unless disabled by an option, this will close the current shell (EXIT)\n Ctrl + Z   Send the signal SIGTSTP to the current task, which suspends it.\n            To return to it later enter fg \'process name\' (foreground).\n','2015-02-25 07:14:09'),(818,'#pcs -intro','\npcs = personal communication srvc\n\nspecifications for different Personal Communication Services (PCS) systems vary among the different PCS networks. \n    ifk: gsm is one of pcs, and it has its own specification\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 08:37:13'),(819,'#umts -intro -long-list','\nbased on the GSM standards, \numts is a mobile cellular system in the third generation\numts is maintained by 3GPP\n\numts is sometimes compared with cdma2000_networks\nifk: cdma2000 is the opponent of umts\n\numts uses wcdma\n    Currently, WCDMA networks are deployed in UMTS band of around 2 GHz in Europe and Asia, including Japan and America Korea\n    wcdma is now deployed in many countries\n    u have to check wcdma (873) and hspa\n        hspa is deployed over the WCDMA network \n            on the same carrier\n                for high capacity and high speed solution\n            or\n            using another carrier\n        in both case,\n            WCDMA and HSPA can share all the network elements in the core network \n                and the radio network\n                (bts, rnc, sgsn, ggsn)\n            WCDMA and HSPA also share the site base station antennas and antenna cables\n\nThe upgrade WCDMA HSPA requires \n    new software\n    new equipment \n        in the bts\n        RNC \n    to support the rate and higher data capacity\n\nBecause of the shared infrastructure between WCDMA and HSPA\n    the cost of the upgrade WCDMA HSPA is very low \n    compared to the construction of a new stand-alone data network\n\n\nin umts every_entities should be ip\n    simple ip is not enough, many technology are introduced as\n        tunneling, virtualisation( ifk: vlan), ...\n        \'\n        so there are: mobility, security, better qos\n   Each UMTS subscriber has a dedicated home network with \n        which it shares a secret key Ki long term\n        \'\n        hlr keeps track of the current location of all the home network subscribers\n\nMutual authentication between a mobile station and a visited network is carried out \n    with the support of the current GSN (SGSN) and the MSC/VLR\n\nUMTS supports encryption of the radio interface and the integrity protection of signaling messages\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-03-06 04:36:52'),(820,'about-modulation #telec','\nmodulation is a form of change process where we change the input information into a suitable format for the transmission medium\nWe also changed the information by demodulating the signal at the receiving end\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 08:42:43'),(821,'#adc -intro','\nadc: analog to digital converter\nfrom analog, the freq is the most important\n    analog -> [Hz]\nto digital, u say about bits\n    digital -> [bps]\n                bits per second\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 09:25:02'),(822,'#telec -imei -imsi -tmsi -intro','\nimei\n=================\nidentifies a mobile station internationally. a kind serial number\nit is stored in the eir\nit is allocated by the equipment manufacturer\n\'\nIMEI = TAC + FAC + SNR + SP\n    tac: 6 decimal places, centrally assigned   \n    fac: 6 decimal places, assigned by the manufacturer.\n    snr: 6 decimal places, assigned by the manufacturer.\n    sp: 1 decimal place.\n\n\n\n==================\n#imsi-------------\ndifferent subscribers_identity are used, and they are used in different phases of call setup\n\'\nimsi is the first nb_identity of the subscriber\n    it is assigned permanently to that subscriber\n\nEach registered user is uniquely identified by its imsi\n\nimsi is stored in the sim\nit is 15digits\nThe IMSI is used to acquire the details of the mobile \n    in the HLR or \n    in the VLR\n\'\nimsi = mcc + mnc + msin\n    mcc: 3 decimal places, internationally standardized.\n    mnc: 2 decimal places, for unique identification of mobile network within the country.\n    msin: Maximum 10 decimal places, identification number of the subscriber in the home mobile network\n\nAfter the subscriber’s IMSI has been initialized on the system\n    the TMSI can be used for sending backward and forward across the network to identify the subscriber\n    \'\n    The system automatically changes the TMSI at regular intervals\n        for the security of the subscriber\n        with the lai    \n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-28 04:03:18'),(817,'#gsm -history','\n1982	CEPT establishes a GSM group in order to develop the standards for a pan-European cellular mobile system.\n\n1985	A list of recommendations to be generated by the group is accepted.\n\n1986	Field tests are performed to test the different radio techniques proposed for the air interface.\n\n1987	Time Division Multiple Access (TDMA) is chosen as the access method (with Frequency Division Multiple Access [FDMA]). The initial Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) is signed by telecommunication operators representing 12 countries.\n\n1988	GSM system is validated.\n\n1989	The responsibility of the GSM specifications is passed to the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI).\n\n1990	Phase 1 of the GSM specifications is delivered.\n\n1991	Commercial launch of the GSM service occurs. The DCS1800 specifications are finalized.\n\n1992	The addition of the countries that signed the GSM Memorandum of Understanding takes place. Coverage spreads to larger cities and airports.\n\n1993	Coverage of main roads\' GSM services starts outside Europe.\n\n1994	Data transmission capabilities launched. The number of networks rises to 69 in 43 countries by the end of 1994.\n\n1995	Phase 2 of the GSM specifications occurs. Coverage is extended to rural areas.\n\n1996	June: 133 network in 81 countries operational.\n\n1997	July: 200 network in 109 countries operational, around 44 million subscribers worldwide.\n\n1999	Wireless Application Protocol came into existence and 130 countries operational with 260 million subscribers.\n\n2000	General Packet Radio Service(GPRS) came into existence.\n\n2001	As of May 2001, over 550 million people were subscribers to mobile telecommunications.\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 08:24:26'),(823,' -fdma-tdma','\nhttp://www.tutorialspoint.com/gsm/gsm_specification.htm\nspecification of gsm is about:\n    modulation type\n    access methods\n    transmission rate\n    freq band\n    channel spacing\n    speech coding\n    duplex distance\n\n===============================================================\nmodulation type:\n    gsm uses gmsk(gaussian modulation shift keying)\n\naccess method\n    GSM chose a combination of TDMA/FDMA as its method\n        FDMA part involves the division by frequency of the total 25 MHz bandwidth \n            into 124 carrier frequencies of 200 kHz bandwidth.\n        one or more frequ are assigned to one bs\n            each carrier will be divided into 8 by the tdma\n\nfreq band\n    the uplink freq range:  933 - 960 MHz\n    the downlink freq range:    890 - 915 MHz\n    remember the value 25Mhz\n\nchannel spacing \n    it is the separation between adjacent carrier frequencies\n    in gsm it is 200kHz\n\nspeech coding:\n    gsm uses lpc,\n        its purpose is to reduce the bit rate\n        provide a filter which mimics the voice\n        Speech is encoded at 13 kbps\n\nframe duration:\n    in gsm it_s 4.615 mS\n\nSpeech channels per RF channel: 8\n\nDuplex Technique: fdd (previously the wcdma)\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 14:21:10'),(824,'#vim -unmap-arrows',NULL,NULL,'\nmap <Left> <Nop>\nmap <Right> <Nop>\nmap <Up> <Nop>\nmap <Down> <Nop>\n','2015-02-25 12:35:51'),(825,'#1G -about','\ndisadvantage:\n============================\nevery thing is analog\n    then not robust to interference\nmany countries have their own standards\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 12:53:13'),(826,'#2G -advantage','\nuses advanced modulation\nimproved spectral utilization\nsms is included\nImproved efficiency of access\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-28 17:13:43'),(827,'#gsm -freq-range','\nSystem 			P-GSM (Primary) 	E-GSM (Extended) 	GSM 1800		GSM 1900\n====================================================================================\nFreq Uplink 	890-915MHz			880-915MHz			1710-1785Mhz	1850-1910MHz\nFreq Downlink 	935-960MHz			925-960MHz			1805-1880Mhz	1930-1990MHz\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 13:10:05'),(828,'#pstn -intro','\nThe PSTN consists of telephone lines, fiber optic cables, microwave transmission links, \n    cellular networks, communications satellites, and undersea telephone cables, \n    all interconnected by _switching_centers_\n    \'\n    thus allowing any telephone in the world to communicate with any other.\n\npstn is like the internet for the telephones\n\n               +----+                +----+\n               | co +----------------+ co |\n               +--+-+--------+       +--+-+\n                  |          |          |\n                  |          |          |\n                  |          |          |\n                  |          |          |\n                +-+--+       +----------+----+\n                | co |                  | co |\n            +-->+----+  <<<-----+       +----+\n            |      ^            |\n     +------+      |            |\n     |phone1|      |            |\n     +------+ +----+-+          +------+\n              |phone2| ........ |phoneN|\n              +------+          +------+\n\npstn is the network of co\n\nnadp is a sort of protocol used in pstn\n  +----+                                      +----+\n  | co |---->>....co....co...------------>>   | co +-------phoneB\n  +----+                                      +----+\n     ^\n     |\n  +--+---+\n  |phoneA|\n  +------+\nif phoneA wants to contact phoneB\n    it uses nadp\n\n\n\n                                                           +--- this is a box in which\n                                                           |      the co_ctrl will stop\n   +------+                                  +------+      |\n   |  co  | <<----.... co .......co......<<--+  co  |      |\n   +------+                                  +--+---+      |\n                                                |          |                +----house------+\n                                                |   +--+   |                |               |\n                                                |   |  |   +---------+------+        +-----+|\n                                                +---+  +-------------|demarc+--------+phone||\n                                                    |  |             +------+        +-----+|\n                                                    |  |                    +---------------+\n                                                    |  |\n                                               +----+--+\n                                               +-telephone_pole\n\ntelephon_company will be responsible for communication from the co and pstn till the demarc_box\nif sth wrong happen from the demarc_box till the phone, it will not be the responsible of the\n    telephony_company\n\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 17:02:10'),(829,'#telec -isdn -intro','\nit is a set of communication standards for _simultaneous_ digital transmission of: \n    voice, video, data, \n    and other network services over the traditional circuits of the pstn\n	over a _single_line_\n                                          |\n                                    tel_operator_cloud uses\n                                      digital inside the \n                                           cloud\n                                           |\n                                           |                    |\n                                       digital               analog\n          digital                          |                    |\n            |                     +-------------------+         |\n      +--+  |        +-----+ |    |+-----------------+|         |         +-------+\n      |pc+------>>   |modem+-->>  ||  tel_op_cloud   |+------------>>     | modem |\n      +--+  |        +-----+ |    |+-----------------+|                   +---+---+\n                             |    +-------------------+                       |\n                             |                                                |\n                           analog                                       ------|-----digital--\n                                                                              |\n                 +----------------------+                                     |\n                 |+--------------------+|              |          +-----+     |\n                 ||      internet      ||      <<-----------------+ isp |  <<-+\n                 |+--------------------+|              |          +-----+\n                 +----------------------R            digital\n                                                       |\n\nisdn consist of communication between digital to digital end\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 17:37:42'),(830,'#gsm -cgi','\ncgi = mcc + mnc + lac + ci\n      |              |\n      +--+-----------+\n         +-- lai\n\nmcc: 3decimal places\nmnc: 2decimal places\nlac: min 5decimal places or max 8 decimal placemcc: 3decimal places\nmnc: 2decimal places\nlac: min 5decimal places or max 8 decimal placess\n\nwith the help of cgi, calls are internationally defined in a unique way.\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-26 02:57:02'),(832,'#gsm -cell -intro','one BTS covers one cell.\neach cell is given one cgi to identify the cell',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 14:44:57'),(833,'#telec -msc -intro #gsm','\nperforms all the switching functions for all mobile stations in the area which is covered\n    by its bss\nmsc switching is based on isdn_switching\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 17:27:51'),(834,'#gsm -location-area -lai','\nA group of cells form a Location Area\nEach Location Area is assigned a lai\nEach Location Area is served by one or more BSCs\n\neach location-area has its own lai\nthe laiis internationally unique as follows\n    lai = cc + mnc + lac\n        cc:  3 decimal places.\n        mnc: 2 decimal places.\n        lac: maximum 5 decimal places or maximum twice 8 bits coded in hexadecimal (LAC < FFFF)',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 15:26:48'),(835,'#gsm -msisdn -msrn -intro','\n====================\n#msisdn---------------------\nThe real telephone number of a mobile station is the msisdn\nIt is assigned to the subscriber (him|her sim)\n\'\nit follows the isdn number plan\n    so it has the following structure:\n    \'\n    msisdn = cc + ndc + sn\n\n#end_msisdn\n\n\n\n\n=================\n#msrn------------------------\nassigned by the locally responsible VLR to each mobile station in its area. \nCalls are also routed to the MS by using the MSRN.\nThe MSRN has same structure as the MSISDN\n    msrn = cc + ndc + snr\n        cc: of the visited area\n        ndc: of the visited area\n        snr: serial number of the phone doesn_t change\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 15:16:54'),(836,'#gsm -identifiers-addresses','\nthose are the most important identifiers and addresses in gsm:\n==============================\nimei\nimsi\nmsisdn\nmsrn\ntmsi\nlai\nlmsi\nci\nauc\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-26 03:07:57'),(837,'#gsm -lmsi','\nThe VLR can assign an additional searching key to each mobile station within its area to accelerate database access\n    this unique key is the lmsi\nThe LMSI is assigned when the mobile station registers with the VLR and is also sent to the HLR\nlmsi is 4bytes\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 15:50:57'),(838,'-about-analog-signals','\nifk: analog signal is used when a signal has to be carried to long distance\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 15:57:40'),(839,'#gsm -bts -intro','\nhas a set of Transceivers (TRXs) to communicate with mobiles in its area\n\nOne BTS covers one or more than one cell\n\nBTS is connected to the BSC through Abis Interface which is 2Mbps\n\nBTS transmits and receives voice at 13kbps over air interface to the mobiles.\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 16:03:18'),(840,'#gsm -bsc -intro','\nSeveral BTSs are connected to the BSC\n\nBSC manages: \n    channel allocation, \n    handovers \n    release of channels at connected BTS\n\n\n            +---+       |        +-----+       |        +-----+\n            |bts| ------------>> | bsc |-------------->>| msc |\n            +---+       |        +-----+       |        +-----+\n                        |                      |\n                    abis_interf             a_interf\n\nBSC has the entire database of cell parameters associated with the BTSs\n\nNo mobile data is stored in the BSC\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 16:08:47'),(841,'#gsm -rate -trau -intro','\n\n            13kbps            16kbps          16kbps                64kbps\n               |                |               |                      |\n               |                |               |                      |\n     +----+    |    +-------+   |     +-----+   |    +------------+    |       +-------+\n     | MS +------>> |  BTS  +------>> | BSC +------> | MSC & TRAU +--------->> | PSTN  |\n     +----+         +-------+         +-----+        +------------+            +-------+\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 16:12:35'),(842,'#gsm -plmn -intro','\nthe specific purpose of plmn is providing land mobile telecommunications services to the public\nplmn must be connected to pstn in order to route calls\n\nA PLMN is identified by the mcc and the mnc\n\nplmn interconnects with other plmn_s and other pstn_s\n    or with internet_srvc\n\nThe area covered by one network operator(ex: telma) is called PLMN. \n\nA PLMN can contain one or more MSCs.\n\nifk: gsm is one of the numerous plmn\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-28 14:36:39'),(843,'#telec -pots -intro','\nit is the standard service offering from telephone companies from 1876 until about 1960\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-25 17:41:35'),(844,'#gsm -tmsi','\nit is stored in the vlr, and it is not passed in the hlr\ntmsi has significance in the area handled by the VLR only.\nTogether with the current location area, TMSI allows a subscriber to be identified uniquely and it can consist of up to 4x8 bits.\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-26 02:53:21'),(845,'#gsm -vlr -intro','\nit contains a 2nd db for the mgt of the mobile_s_subscribers located in the vlr area\n    so the load of hlr(1st db) is minimized\n\nit ctrl the roaming of ms in an msc assigned to that ms\nmust contact the hlr for handling the calls\n\n\nresponsible for the current location of a subscriber\n    then assign a tmsi \nassign an additional searching key(lmsi) to each mobile station within its area to accelerate database access.\n\nthe information in the db of the vlr are:\n    all the subscriber numbers which are active\n    imsi\n    \n                          +--------+\n                          | +-----+|\n                          | | hlr ||\n +-----+-------+          | +-----+|           +-------+-------+\n |     |  msc  +----------+--------+-----------+  msc  |       |\n |     +-------+                               +-------+       |\n |                                                             |\n +-----+-------+                               +-------+       |\n       |  vlr  |                               |  vlr  +-------+\n       +-------+                               +-------+\n\nMSC communicates with HLR for subscribers coming from different MSCs.\n    If the subscriber is found valid, \n        then it registers the subscriber in the VLR\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-28 03:19:56'),(846,'#gsm -auc -intro','\nauthentication is the process by which a sim is verified\nsecret data and algorithm are stored in the auc.\nauc is associated with the hlr\n\n    +----+         +-----+    +-----+     +------+\n    | ms +->....-->| msc +--->| hlr +---->| auc  |\n    +----+         +-----+    +-----+     +------+\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-26 03:09:45'),(847,'#gsm -eir -intro','\ncontains a database which has a series of IMEI\n	which is stored with relevant classifications\n	\'\n	white list:\n		contains the IMEI of type approved mobiles\n	black list:\n		contains IMEIs which should be barred because \n			either they are stolen or are not functioning properly\n	grey list:\n		List of IMEIs which are to be evaluated \n			before they are put in black list\n\nMSC asks the Mobile to send its IMEI\n	MSC then checks the validity of IMEI with the EIR\n\n         +--+                     +-----+      +-----+\n         |ms+---.......-----------+ msc +------+ eir |\n         +--+                     +-----+      +-----+\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-26 06:44:04'),(848,'#gsm -bc  -intro','\nit Generates the billing statement for each subscriber\n\nBC may be directly connected to the MSC or through a mediation device\n\nmsc sends cdr to the bc\n\nbc generates the bill according:\n    to the destination called and the call duration\n    to the units set\n    to the template of pulse rates\n                                      +-------------+\n                                      |templates for|\n                                      |  unit costs |\n                                      +-----+-------+\n                                            |\n                                            v\n    +----+              +-----+           +----+\n    | ms +--->.....---->| msc +---------> | bc +------>  call_cost\n    +----+              +-----+  cdr      +----+\n\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-26 03:50:14'),(849,'#gsm -noc -omc -important','\nomc = noc\n\nIt is the central monitoring and remote maintenance centre for all network elements\n\nOMC has links to BSCs and MSCs\n\n                     +---+-----+    +---+                 +----+-----+\n                     |bts|     |    |bsc+----+            |    | msc |\n                     +---+  +--+----+---+    |            |    +-----+\n                     +---+--+  |             |  +---------+\n                     |bts|     |             |  |+-------+|\n                     +---+     |             +--+|  omc  ||\n                     +---+-----+             |  |+-------+|\n                     |bts|          +---+    |  +----+----+----+-----+\n                     +---+      +---+bsc+----+       |         | msc |\n                     +---+      | +-+---+            |         +-----+\n                     |bts|      | |                  |\n                     +---+------+ |             +----+------+\n                     +---+        |             |           |\n                     |...|        |             |           |\n                     +---+--------+          +--+--+     +--+--+\n                                             | p c |     | p c |\n                                             +-----+     +-----+\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-26 03:59:54'),(850,'#gprs-intro #gsm ','\ngprs is also known as a gsm-ip\n\nit allows the subscriber to make voice calls, and access internet on the go\ngprs is also known as a gsm-ip\ngprs add those nexts to the gsm network:\n    pcu\n    sgsn: the msc for the gprs_network\n    bg: a gateway to other plmn\n    Intra-PLMN backbone:\n        an IP based network inter-connecting all the GPRS element\n\n\n\nanother type of intro:\n======================\nGPRS relies also on re-transmission and data integrity protocols to ensure that \n    data packets transmitted over the radio air interface are not lost or corrupted\n\nGPRS introduces packet data transmission to the mobile subscriber\n    This packet mode technique uses multi-slot technology together with coding schemes (CS-1 to CS-4)\n        that increase the data rates up to 160 kbit/s\n\ngprs is designed to work within an existing gsm\n	with additional packet switching nodes\n	\'\n	This packet mode technique uses multi-slot technology\n		to increase the data rates up to 160 kbit/s.\n\nThe GPRS system uses the physical radio channels as defined for GSM.\n	but it is called pdch\n\nA physical channel used by GPRS is called a pdch\n    The operator can define 0-8 dedicated PDCHs per cell. \n    The first dedicated PDCH in the cell is always a mpdch\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-03-06 00:55:49'),(851,'#gprs-gsm -architecture','\n             +-----------------------------+\n             |            +-----+          |            +------------------------------+\n             |            | bts +----+     |            |                              |\n             |            +-----+    |     |            |                              |\n             |    +-----+            | +---+-+        +-+---+            +------+      |\n             |    | bts +------------+-+ bsc +--------+ msc |            | gmsc +----------isdn\n             |    +-----+            | +---+-+        +-+---+            +------+      |\n             |                       |     |            |                              |\n             |             +-----+   |     |            |        gsm_core              |\n             |             | bts +---+     |            |                              |\n             |             +-----+         |            |     +-----+                  |\n             |    g s m _ r a n            |            +-----+ hlr +------------------+\n             +-----------------------------+                  | auc |\n              +---------------------------+             +-----+ eir +--------------+\n              |  u                        |             |     +-----+              |\n              |      +-------+            |             |                          |\n              |  t   | nodeB +------+     |             |                          |     +----------+\n              |      +-------+      |  +--+--+         ++-----+         +--------+ |     |+--------+|\n              |  r                  +--+ rnc +---------+ sgsn |         |  ggsn  +-------+|internet||\n              |      +-------+      |  +--+--+         ++-----+         +--------+ |     |+--------+|\n              |  a   | nodeB +------+     |             |                          |     +----------+\n              |      +-------+            |             |     gprs_core            |\n              |  n                        |             |                          |\n              +---------------------------+             +--------------------------+\n\n\n\n                  +-------+                   +---+\n                  |msc/vlr+---------D---------+hlr|\n                  +-------+-----+     +-------+---+\n                  |             |     |\n                  A            Gs     Gr\n                  |             |     |\n                  |             |     |\n     +--+         +---+        ++-----+          +----+             +---+\n     |ms+---------+bss+---Gb---+ sgsn +---Gn-----+ggsn+-----Gi------+pdn|\n     +--+         +---+        ++-----+          +----+             +---+\n                                |     |\n                                |     |\n                               Gn     Gp\n                                |     |\n                                |     |\n                 +----+---------+     +------+----+\n                 |sgsn|                      |ggsn|\n                 +----+                      +----+\n\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-28 14:29:35'),(852,'#telec #gprs #gsm -gmsc-intro','\nProvides interconnection between \n    the UMTS core network \n    and \n    external PSTN/ISDN networks\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-26 06:14:03'),(853,'#gsm -msc -intro','\n          +-----+                                       +---+\n          | bsc +--------+                       +------+hlr|\n          +-----+        |                       |      +---+\n                         |     +-----+           |\n          +-----+    ----+-----+ msc +-----------+\n          | ... |        |     +-----+           |\n          +-----+        |           |           |      +---+\n                         |           |---------+ +------+hlr|\n          +-----+        |    ^     ++-----+   |        +---+\n          | bsc +--------+    |     | pstn |   |\n          +-----+             |     +---+--+   +---------------------fixed_line\n                 |            |         |\n                 +----+-------+  +------+-------------------+\n                      |          |                          |\n      a_interf   -----+    +-----+-----+               +----+------+\n                           |fixed_phone|               |fixed_phone|\n                           +-----------+               +-----------+\n\ncentral about:\n    switching the calls\n    maintaining the calls\n    release the calls\n\ncontains a database for all subscribers and their associated features\n\nMSC is weighted on the number of subscribers it can support\n\nWhen there is more capacity, there are more than one MSCs\n    then there is a concept of gmsc\n    then the schema of the network is not like the one before\n\n         +---+        +-----+ \n         |bsc+--------+ msc +----+\n         +---+        +-----+    |   +------+       +------+\n                                 +---| gmsc +-------+ pstn |\n                                 |   +------+       +------+\n         +---+        +-----+    |\n         |bsc+--------+ msc +----+\n         +---+        +-----+\n\n\nmsc is connected to many other devices\nhere it defines more and shows with more interfaces:\n\n                 +-----+        +-----+          +-----+\n                 | omc |        | vlr |          | eir |\n                 +-----+-----+  +-----+          +-----+\n                             |        |          |               +----------+\n         +---------+         +---+    B          F               | hlr .... |\n         | bss ... |             |    |          |               +----------+\n         +---------+-----A-------+----+-----+----+-------C-------+\n                                 |   m s c  |\n                                 +----------+--E---+\n               +------------+----+                 +----------+\n               |  psn/isdn  |                      | msc .... |\n               |   network  |                      +----------+\n               +------------+\n\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-28 14:55:04'),(854,'#gsm -hlr -intro','\nMSC has a database which is stored in hlr\nthat database contains:\n    imsi\n    location information\n        then enabling calls routing from sgsn|msc to ms\n\n    all permanent subscribers\n    describes the subscriber’s profile\n        basic features             -+-----of the subscriber\n        supplementary services     -+\n\nMSC communicates with the HLR to get data for subscribers on call\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-28 02:40:23'),(855,'#gsm -channels','\ndivided into 2:\n    physical channels\n        one time slot on one carrier is a physical_channel\n    logical channels\n        information carried by the physical_channel is \n            the logical_channel\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-02-27 12:58:37'),(856,'#gsm -channels -sum_up','\n                                           +----------------+\n                                           +--gsm_channels--+\n                                           +--------+-------+\n                                                    |\n                                                    |\n                  +------------------+              |                +-----------------+\n                  +-physical_channel-+--------------+----------------+ logical_channel |\n                  +------------------+                               +--------+--------+\n                                                                              |\n                                                                  +-----------+--------+\n                                                                  |                    |\n                                                               +--+--+              +--+--+\n                                                               | tch |              | cch |\n                                                               +--+--+              +--+--+\n                                                                  |                    |\n                                                                  |                    |\n                                                          +-----+ |  +-----+           |\n                                                          |tch/f+-+--+tch/h|           |\n                                                          +-----+    +-----+           |\n                                                                               +-------+---------+