llocated in eight time slots\n        which is not likely to be allowed by network operators\n\ntransmission in gprs is like the transmission in the ip_network\n    so to reach the target, packets have to go through many nodes\n    that can produce delays affecting the qos\n\nThe protocols between the BSS and the SGSN support mainly asynchronous\n    making it a challenge to implement real-time interactive traffic\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-03-05 04:43:47'),(902,'#gsm -limitation','\nmultiple users share the same bandwidth\n    the transmission can encounter interference\n\n    Because GSM is the same network worldwide, \n        users are not charged a roaming fee for international calls. \n            However, most providers still charge a service fee on international calls\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-03-05 05:36:33'),(903,'#gsm -voice-call-log','\n-> The Mobile Station is requesting connection\n-> The BTS is sending request data to the BSC\n-> The BSC is sending request data to the MSC\n-> The MSC is checking registration and subscribed services of calling MS\n-> The MSC is checking registration and location of called MS\n-> The MSC is sending request data to the GMSC\n-> The GMSC is sending data to another network\n-> The GMSC is requesting registration and location data of called MS\n-> The HLR is checking authentication, validation and location of called MS\n-> The HLR is sending registration and location data to the GMSC\n-> The GMSC is sending location data to the MSC\n-> The MSC is sending location data for call set-up to the BSC\n-> The BSC is paging called MS\n-> Connection established\n-> CDR generation: MOC,POC\n-> Connection terminated\n-> CDR generation: MTC,PTC\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-03-05 05:37:22'),(904,'#gsm -call-ms_to_pstn',NULL,NULL,'\nThe MSC/VLR receives the message of a call request.\n\nThe MSC/VLR checks if the mobile station is authorized to access the network. \n    If so, the mobile station is activated. \n    If the mobile station is not authorized, service will be denied.\n\nMSC/VLR analyzes the number and initiates a call setup with the PSTN.\n\nMSC/VLR asks the corresponding BSC to allocate a traffic channel (a radio channel and a time slot).\n\nThe BSC allocates the traffic channel and passes the information to the mobile station.\n\nThe called party answers the call and the conversation takes place.\n\nThe mobile station keeps on taking measurements of the radio channels\n    in the present cell and neighboring cells and passes the information to the BSC. \n    The BSC decides if handover is required, \n        if so, a new traffic channel is allocated to the mobile station and the handover is performed. \n        If handover is not required, the mobile station continues to transmit in the same frequency.\n','2015-03-05 08:40:29'),(905,'#gsm -call-pstn_to_ms','\nThe gmsc receives the call and queries the HLR for the information needed to route the call to the serving MSC/VLR.\n\nThe GMSC routes the call to the MSC/VLR.\n\nThe MSC checks the VLR for the location area of the MS.\n\nThe MSC contacts the MS via the BSC through a broadcast message, that is, through a paging request.\n\nThe MS responds to the page request.\n\nThe BSC allocates a traffic channel and sends a message to the MS to tune to the channel. \n    The MS generates a ringing signal and, after the subscriber answers, the speech connection is established.\n\nHandover, \n    if required, takes place, as discussed in the earlier case.\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-03-05 08:43:11'),(906,'#linux -create-partition#ntfs',NULL,NULL,'\nthis next cmd is taken from gparted\n    when it tries to format to a ntfs_partition\n    \'\n    mkntfs -Q -v -L \"\" /dev/sdb2\n','2015-03-05 08:45:16'),(907,'#gsm -protocol-stack','\n                     |                     |                        |\n                cm   |                     |                        |        cm\n          -----------+---------------------+------------------------+---------------\n                     |                     |                        |\n                mm   |                     |                        |     mm\n                     |                     |                        |\n          -----------+---------------------+------------------------+---------------\n                     |                     |              dtap      |   dtap\n                     |                     |  rr          bssmap    |   bssmap\n          -----------+---------------------+------------------------+---------------\n                rr   |    rr        btsm   |              sccp      |   sccp\n                     |                     |  btsm                  |\n                     |                     |              mtp3      |   mtp3\n          -----------+---------------------+------------------------+---------------\n                     |                     |                        |\n             lapdm   |   lapdm     lapd    |  lapd        mtp2      |   mtp2\n                     |                     |                        |\n          -----------+---------------------+------------------------+--------------\n                     |                     |                        |\n             gsm_rf  |   gsm_rf   layer1   |  layer1      mtp1      |  mtp1\n\n                    Um                   Abis                       A\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-03-05 09:17:28'),(908,'#edge -intro -long-list','\nedge introduces a new modulation technique,\n    as well as protocol enhancements for transmitting packets over the radio\n\nedge is _almost_ a 3g\n    the use of new modulation technique increased dramatically throughput and capacity gains enabling 3G services\n\nNo changes are needed to the existing core network infrastructure to support EDGE\n\nnine mcs are introduced (mcs1 to mcs9)\n    4 of them are using gmsk\n    5 uses 8_psk_modulation\n\nwhat edge technologies required:\n============================================\n    MS should be EDGE enabled\n    in bts: the hardware in bts is Edge enabled\n    in bsc: Definitions for EDGE timeslots needs to be done in BSC\n    in gsn: Definitions for Edge need to be defined in GSN\n\nbenefits:\n============================================\n    Increases the capacity and triples the data rate of GPRS\n    Enables new multimedia services\n        ifk: mms\n    Harmonization with WCDMA\n    Short-term benefits: Capacity and performance\n    Easy implementation on a GSM/GPRS network\n\nfor the user, it means:\n============================================\n    Streaming applications\n    Very high speed downloads\n    Quicker MMS\n    Video conference, Remote presentations\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-03-06 01:27:39'),(909,'dual-ip-stack -intro','\nused for for IPv6 migration\n\nIt helps to establish communication between your IPv6 network \n    and the native IPv4 hosts and applications\n\nA dual-stack node has support for both protocol versions(ipv6 and ipv4)\n',NULL,NULL,'2015-03-07 15:30:26'),(913,'#java -jtabbedpane -intro',NULL,NULL,'\nto put many jpanelXX in sth like this:\n\n            +-------------------------------------------------+\n            | jframe                                          |\n            +-------------------------------------------------+\n            |+------+------+---------------------------------+|\n            ||tab01 |tab02 |tab03 |                          ||\n            |+------+      +---------------------------------+|\n            ||                                               ||\n            ||    content of tab02                           ||\n            ||        this is a jpanel02                     ||\n            ||                                               ||\n            |+-----------------------------------------------+|\n            +-------------------------------------------------+\n\n\n\nclass extPanel01 ext JPanel {                                  -----+\n    public void paintComponent(Graphics g){               